[{"location":"getting_started/#Getting-started","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"Install SymBoltz.jl and load it with","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"using ModelingToolkit\nimport SymBoltz","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/#1.-Define-the-model","page":"Getting started","title":"1. Define the model","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"The first step is to define our cosmological model. This is a symbolic representation of the variables and equations that describe the various components in the universe, such as the theory of gravity (like general relativity) and particle species (like the cosmological constant, cold dark matter, photons and baryons). It will be used both to create the numerical problem to solve, and to access variables in its solution.","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"To get started, we will simply load the standard ΛCDM model:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"@named M = SymBoltz.ΛCDM()\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"The symbolic model has a hierarchical structure, with multiple subsystems representing different components of the Einstein-Boltzmann system:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"using Plots\nplot(M)","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"In this case, the components are:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"Symbol Component\ng spacetime metric (g_munu)\nG gravity\nγ photons\nν massless neutrinos\nc cold dark matter\nb baryons\nh massive neutrinos\nΛ cosmological constant\nrec recombination","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"The hierarchical structure of the whole symbolic model can be inspected interactively as a ModelingToolkit system by evaluating M, M.<TAB>, M.G and so on (with TAB-completion). For example, to see all equations for the theory of gravity:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"equations(M.G)","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"See TODO to learn more about the model representation and how to define extended cosmological models.","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/#2.-Build-the-problem","page":"Getting started","title":"2. Build the problem","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"The next step is to create a cosmological problem from the symbolic model. This separates the full model into sequential computational stages, like the background and perturbation systems.","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"prob = SymBoltz.CosmologyProblem(M)\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/#3.-Solve-the-problem","page":"Getting started","title":"3. Solve the problem","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"Finally, we set our desired cosmological parameters and wavenumbers, and solve the problem:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"pars = [\n    M.γ.Ω0 => 5e-5\n    M.c.Ω0 => 0.27\n    M.b.Ω0 => 0.05\n    M.ν.Neff => 3.0\n    M.g.h => 0.7\n    M.b.rec.Yp => 0.25\n]\nks = 10 .^ range(-3, 0, length=100) / SymBoltz.k0 # TODO: improve on units\nsol = SymBoltz.solve(prob, pars, ks)","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"To solve only the background, you can simply omit the ks argument: SymBoltz.solve(prob, pars, ks).","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/#4.-Access-the-solution","page":"Getting started","title":"4. Access the solution","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"You are now free to do whatever you want with the solution object. It can be called like","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"sol(t, var) to access the background variable(s) var as a function of the conformal time(s) t, or\nsol(k, t, var) to access the perturbed variable(s) var as a function of the wavenumber(s) k and conformal time(s) t.","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"This will interpolate linearly in log(k), and with the ODE solver's interpolator in t.","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"For example, to get the reduced Hubble function E(t) = H(t)  H_0 for 1000 log-spaced conformal times:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"ts = exp.(range(log.(extrema(sol[SymBoltz.t]))..., length=1000)) # TODO: replace with M.t\nEs = sol(ts, M.g.E)","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"Similarly, to get Phi(kt) for the 100 wavenumbers we solved for and the same 1000 log-spaced conformal times:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"Φs = sol(ks, ts, M.g.Φ)","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"This can be plotted with using Plots; plot(log10.(ts), transpose(Φs)), but this is even easier with the included plot recipe:","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"using Plots\nplot(sol, ks[begin:5:end], log10(M.g.a), M.g.Φ) # lg(a) vs. Φ for every 5th wavenumber","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"We can also calculate the power spectrum for a desired species (here: cold dark matter with M.c):","category":"page"},{"location":"getting_started/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"Ps = SymBoltz.P(sol, M.c, ks)\nplot(log10.(ks), log10.(Ps); xlabel=\"lg(k)\", ylabel=\"lg(P)\", label=nothing)","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/#Automatic-differentiation","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"This tutorial shows how to compute the (cold dark matter) power spectrum P(k theta) and its (logarithmic) derivatives","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"fracpartial lg Ppartial lg theta_i","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"using automatic differentiation with ForwardDiff.jl. This technique can also differentiate any other quantity.","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/#1.-Wrapping-the-evaluation","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"1. Wrapping the evaluation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"We must first decide which parameters theta the power spectrum P(k theta) will be considered a function of. To do so, let us write a small wrapper function that calculates the power spectrum as a function of the parameters (Omega_gamma 0 Omega_c0 Omega_b0 N_textrmeff h Y_p), following the Getting started tutorial:","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"using ModelingToolkit\nimport SymBoltz\n\n@named M = SymBoltz.ΛCDM()\nprob = SymBoltz.CosmologyProblem(M)\n\n# define ordering and values of parameters\nθ_syms = [M.γ.Ω0, M.c.Ω0, M.b.Ω0, M.ν.Neff, M.g.h, M.b.rec.Yp] # symbolic indices\nθ_strs = [\"Ωγ0\" \"Ωc0\" \"Ωb0\" \"Neff\" \"h\" \"Yp\"] # plot labels\nθ0 = [5e-5, 0.27, 0.05, 3.0, 0.7, 0.25] # numerical values\n\nP(k, θ) = SymBoltz.P(SymBoltz.solve(prob, θ_syms .=> θ, k), M.c, k)","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"It is now easy to evaluate the power spectrum:","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"ks = 10 .^ range(-3, 0, length=100) / SymBoltz.k0 # TODO: improve on units\nPs = P(ks, θ0)","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"This can be plotted with","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"using Plots\nplot(log10.(ks), log10.(Ps); xlabel = \"lg(k)\", ylabel = \"lg(P)\", label = nothing)","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/#2.-Calculate-the-derivatives","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"2. Calculate the derivatives","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"To get partial lg P  partial lg theta, we can simply pass the wrapper function P(k, θ) through ForwardDiff.jacobian:","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"using ForwardDiff\nlgP(lgθ) = log10.(P(ks, 10 .^ lgθ)) # ForwardDiff.jacobian needs an array -> array function\ndlgP_dlgθs = ForwardDiff.jacobian(lgP, log10.(θ0))","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"The matrix element dlgP_dlgθs[i, j] now contains partial lg P(k_i)  partial lg theta_j. We can plot them all at once:","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"plot(log10.(ks), dlgP_dlgθs; xlabel = \"lg(k)\", ylabel = \"∂ lg(P) / ∂ lg(θᵢ)\", labels = \"θᵢ=\" .* θ_strs)","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/#Get-values-and-derivatives-together","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Get values and derivatives together","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"The above example showed how to calculate the power spectrum values and their derivatives through two separate calls. If you need both, it is faster to calculate them simultaneously with the package DiffResults.jl:","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"using DiffResults\n\nPres = DiffResults.JacobianResult(ks, θ0) # allocate buffer for value+derivatives for a function with θ0-sized input and ks-sized output\nPres = ForwardDiff.jacobian!(Pres, lgP, log10.(θ0)) # evaluate value+derivatives of lgP(log10.(θ0)) and store the results in Pres\nlgPs = DiffResults.value(Pres) # extract value\ndlgP_dlgθs = DiffResults.jacobian(Pres) # extract derivatives\n\np1 = plot(log10.(ks), lgPs; ylabel = \"lg(P)\", label = nothing)\np2 = plot(log10.(ks), dlgP_dlgθs; xlabel = \"lg(k)\", ylabel = \"∂ lg(P) / ∂ lg(θᵢ)\", labels = \"θᵢ=\" .* θ_strs)\nplot(p1, p2, layout=(2, 1), size = (600, 600))","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/#General-approach","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"General approach","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"The technique shown here can be used to calculate the derivative of any SymBoltz.jl output quantity:","category":"page"},{"location":"automatic_differentiation/","page":"Automatic differentiation","title":"Automatic differentiation","text":"Write a wrapper function output(input) that calculates the desired output quantities from the desired input quantities.\nUse ForwardDiff.derivative(output, input) (scalar-to-scalar), ForwardDiff.gradient(output, input) (vector-to-scalar) or ForwardDiff.jacobian(output, input) (vector-to-vector) to evaluate the derivative of output at the values input. Or use the similar functions in DiffResults to calculate the value and derivatives simultaneously.","category":"page"},{"location":"#SymBoltz.jl:-linear-Einstein-Boltzmann-equation-solver","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","text":"SymBoltz.jl is a package for solving the linearized Einstein-Boltzmann system of equations. It is designed to be simple to use, extend and integrate with the wider Julia and SciML ecosystems for scientific analysis.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Features","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"Features","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","text":"Represents the Einstein-Boltzmann system symbolically and solves it numerically (using ModelingToolkit.jl).\nFacilitates development of extended models by representing each component (e.g. theory of gravity and different particle species) as modular blocks of symbolic expressions that are composed to build a custom model.\nDoes not rely on approximations (like the tight coupling, ultra-relativistic fluid and radiation streaming approximations), but solves the resulting stiff equations with implicit integrators (using DifferentialEquations.jl).\nEnables automatic differentiation of any output quantity (using ForwardDiff.jl).\n~~Accelerates the solution over GPUs (using DiffEqGPU.jl).~~\n~~Uses the variable conventions of the seminal paper by Ma and Bertschinger (1995) in most places.~~\nInteroperates with other packages from the wider Julia and SciML ecosystem for parameter fitting, sensitivity analysis, and so on.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Installation","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"Installation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","text":"Launch julia, enter the package manager by hitting ] and enter (one of)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","text":"add https://github.com/hersle/SymBoltz.jl # for usage\ndev https://github.com/hersle/SymBoltz.jl # for development","category":"page"},{"location":"#Usage","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","title":"SymBoltz.jl: linear Einstein-Boltzmann equation solver","text":"TODO: tutorials","category":"page"}]
